Docker, VSCode, GitLab and Office: free alternatives to popular services for programming and work

Hexlet Blog Open source *Git *Development Management *Atlassian *

As a result of the suspension of the work of foreign companies and the disconnection of Russian banks from the Visa and MasterCard payment systems, many programmers have lost access to the usual tools. We talk about free alternatives to products that are no longer available to Russian users on corporate subscriptions or may become such in the near future.

Before you start, it is worth clarifying that some of the services in the collection are still available to users from Russia and Belarus. But given the situation, companies can revoke the license or stop accepting subscription payments at any time. In addition, not all paid services have free alternatives that completely repeat their functionality. Another important point is that shareware foreign services are marked with an asterisk. This means that they can stop working with users from these countries at any time, so it is risky to use them.

Development

Docker and Podman. Both services suspended corporate subscriptions for users from Russia and Belarus.

Alternative:

  • Containerd is a free and open source containerization service. Its development was first done by Docker, but in 2019 it became open - now the developer community is responsible for it, and this is an open standard for any cloud platforms and different OPERATing systems.

GitHub and GitLab. Repository management services have either suspended their corporate subscription (GitLab) or may restrict access to users from Russia in the near future (GitHub).

Alternatives:

  • GitFlic is a shareware (for teams of up to five people) Russian service for managing repositories and joint development. It can hardly be called a full-fledged alternative, but you can be sure that the company, for its part, will not suspend the subscription.

Terraform and Nomad. Open source orchestration systems that greatly facilitate the management of the application architecture. Although the decisions are open-source, their owner, HashiCorp, plans to limit its use for users from Russia.

Alternative:

  • Salt is an open source orchestration system.

Heroku. Cloud PaaS platform for hosting web applications in Ruby, Rails, Node.js, Java, Python, Scala and Clojure.

Alternatives:

  • Back4app is a shareware (basic tariff with limited functionality) platform that allows you to configure authentication, push notifications, REST API, GraphQL API and a scalable database.

  • Dokku is a free mini-version of Heroku that allows you to publish apps using Github Actions. The service consists of three open source components: Docker, Buildstep, and Gitreceive. It is important to note that all components are used in the free version.

Thawte, Digicert and other providers that have revoked SSL certificates from Russian companies and government websites.

Alternative:

  • Let's Encrypt is the most popular non-profit center for issuing free SSL certificates, which are automatically renewed every two to three months. It is worth noting that the authorities can restrict access to it on the territory of Russia and Belarus.

VSCode. One of the most popular code editors that is owned by Microsoft. Earlier, the company announced the suspension of sales in Russia.

Alternatives:

  • VSCodium is a version of VSCode with only free components, without a Microsoft license.

  • Brackets is an open source text editor and IDE for web developers. You can write in HTML, CSS, JavaScript, PHP and Python.

Workflow Services

Jira, Asana, Notion, Trello, Miro, YouTrack. These services for teamwork either closed offices in Russia, or stopped working with Russian companies.

Alternatives:

  • Taiga is a Russian service for managing tasks and sprints. The service can be used free of charge by small teams of up to 15 people.

  • Workzen is a simple online scheduler for tracking tasks from MTS.

  • Shtab is a Russian free service for teams of up to five people, which allows you to manage tasks and reports.

Slack, Microsoft Team. Both messengers suspended payment for corporate subscriptions, and Slack stopped registering new users in Russia.

Alternative:

  • Discord is a free messenger for exchanging text and voice messages. In it, you can create separate channels and mention users. It is worth noting that channels are automatically deleted after a month. Unlike Slack, Discord is an independent organization, so users are not threatened with the departure of the service after the parent company.

Zoom, Skype, Hangouts. These services for organizing conferences have either already stopped accepting payment for a corporate subscription, or plan to do so in the near future.

Alternatives:

  • Jitsi is an open-source service for video conferencing.

  • BigBlueButton is an open source web service for organizing calls that you need to deploy on your servers.

  • Yandex. Teleconferencing is a Russian video conferencing service that allows you to conduct free calls with up to 35 people. It is worth clarifying that to use it you need an account in Yandex-mail, and the service is more of an alternative to Hangouts, rather than Zoom and Skype.

  • Sber Jazz is a free video conferencing service from Sber, similar to Zoom.

Microsoft Office. Microsoft in early March announced the suspension of sales of its products in Russia.

Alternatives:

  • LibreOffice is a free suite of office programs that has both offline and online versions.

  • OpenOffice is a text editor that is distributed free of charge under the Apache license.

Additionally

Figma. Graphic editor for joint design of sites and applications.

Alternative:

  • Lunacy is a free image editor with similar functionality.

Wix, Tilda. Popular website builders that have limited work in Russia.

Alternative:

  • Nethouse is a Russian constructor for creating websites for small online stores and landing pages.

This list of alternatives is not exhaustive. If you know of other free services - write about them in the comments, we will supplement the article.
